"1040":"1040","circa 1100":"circa 1100","1106":"1106","1125":"1125","1158":"1158","1100":"1100","24 May 1140":"24 mei 1140","from 1143 to 1164":"van 1143 to 1164","Teylingen, South Holland, Netherlands":"Teylingen, Zuid-Holland, Nederland","Teylingen, Holland, Netherlands":"Teylingen, Zuid-Holland, Nederland","Slot Brederode, Santpoort,Nederland":"Slot, Noord-Brabant, Nederland","Teijlingen, Holland, Netherlands":"Teijlingen, Zuid-Holland, Nederland"},"en":{"circa 1100–11 Aug 1173":"about 1100–11 August 1173","1100–1173":"1100–1173","1106–1158":"1106–1158","1125–1172":"1125–1172","1131–1173":"1131–1173","1040–1100":"1040–1100","1088–1140":"1088–1140","1088":"1088","1131":"1131","1173":"1173","1140":"1140","1172":"1172","11 Aug 1173":"11 August 1173","1040":"1040","circa 1100":"about 1100","1106":"1106","1125":"1125","1158":"1158","1100":"1100","24 May 1140":"24 May 1140","from 1143 to 1164":"from 1143 to 1164","Teylingen, South Holland, Netherlands":"Teylingen, South Holland, Netherlands","Teylingen, Holland, Netherlands":"Teylingen, South Holland, Netherlands","Slot Brederode, Santpoort,Nederland":"Slot, North Brabant, Netherlands","Teijlingen, Holland, Netherlands":"Teijlingen, South Holland, Netherlands","nameMeanings":[{"name":"van","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Anh, Thanh, Hung, Minh, Vinh, Dung, Hue, Huong, Lan, Quang, Tan, Thuy, Hong, Chi, Hang, Ho, Pok, Sang, Bai, Chin, Ching, Chu, Chuan, Dong.","Vietnamese (<b>Vạn</b>): from the Chinese surname 萬, see   Wan   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Văn</b>): from the Chinese surnames 文 or 聞, see   Wen   2 and 3, and also 5 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Wan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Hong, Yi, Qi, Qiang, Wai, Yiu, Yuk, Chien-Min, Fang, Hin, Jichun, Li, Man, Chung, Min, Yiping, Pak, Sik, Sung Man.  Vietnamese Tin, Bang, Da, Hien, Hoi, Lan, Minh Quang, Sau, Tich, Tung, Yaping, Yuet.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 萬, which means ‘ten thousand’ literally or ‘very great number’ figuratively: (i) from the personal name of Bi Wan (畢萬), an official in the state of Jin (located in present-day Shanxi province). He was said to be a descendant of Bi Gong Gao (known as Duke of Bi), the 15th son of the virtuous King Wen of Zhou (reined 1152–1056  BC ). Bi Wan was later granted the fiefdom of Wei (魏), which in 403  BC  became the state of Wei (located in present-day Shanxi, Shaanxi, Henan and Hebei provinces). Some of his descendants adopted Wei (魏) as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his personal name, as their surname. (ii) from the personal name Wan (萬), style name of Rui Bo (芮伯, the Earl of Rui), an official of the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ), who was granted the fief Rui (located in Ruicheng in Shaanxi province). Some of his descendants inherited Rui (芮), the name of the fief, as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his style name, as their surname. (iii) from the placename Wan (萬), the name of a fief (located in Juxian in Shandong province) granted during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ) to an official in the ancient state of Chu. (iv) from the first element of the name of the Wan Si (萬俟) family, who lived in the downstream areas of the Yellow River during the Northern Qi dynasty (550–577  AD ). (v) from the second element of the name of the Tu Wan (吐萬) family, who are members of the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 完, meaning ‘complete’ in Chinese: (i) said to be borne by the descendants of Huan Zhui, a grandson of the Duke Huan of Song (ruler of the state of Song, died 651  BC ). (ii) from Wan (完), the name of Qu Wan (屈完), an official in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn Period (770–476  BC ). (iii) shortened form of the compound surname Wan-Yan (完顔), a surname from minority ethnic groups such as Juchen ethnic group in ancient northern China."]}]},{"name":"Gerard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’ + <i>hard</i> ‘brave, hardy, strong’. In the later Middle Ages this was a more common name than   Gerald  , with which it was sometimes confused. Nowadays it is less common, surviving mainly among Roman Catholics, in honour of the many saints of this name."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerrard","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Gerard  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Jerrard","meanings":["Rare variant spelling of   Gerard  , probably influenced by the form of the modern surname, if not a transferred use."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gerard van Teijlingen was born about 1100, in Teylingen, South Holland, Netherlands, his father, Gerard I van Teylingen, was 61 and his mother, Catharina Jans van Arkel, was 13. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Cunegonde van der Lecke. In 1143, his occupation is listed as heer van teylingen  in Teijlingen, South Holland, Netherlands. He died on 11 August 1173, in his hometown, at the age of 74."},"et":{"circa 1100–11 Aug 1173":"umbes 1100–11. august 1173","1100–1173":"1100–1173","1106–1158":"1106–1158","1125–1172":"1125–1172","1131–1173":"1131–1173","1040–1100":"1040–1100","1088–1140":"1088–1140","1088":"1088","1131":"1131","1173":"1173","1140":"1140","1172":"1172","11 Aug 1173":"11. august 1173","1040":"1040","circa 1100":"umbes 1100","1106":"1106","1125":"1125","1158":"1158","1100":"1100","24 May 1140":"24. mai 1140","from 1143 to 1164":"1143 kuni 1164","Teylingen, South Holland, Netherlands":"Teylingen, Zuid-Holland, Madalmaad","Teylingen, Holland, Netherlands":"Teylingen, Zuid-Holland, Madalmaad","Slot Brederode, Santpoort,Nederland":"Slot, Noord-Brabant, Madalmaad","Teijlingen, Holland, Netherlands":"Te